<p>The linux kernel struct <a href="http://lxr.free-electrons.com/source/include/linux/fs.h#L1602" rel="nofollow">file_operations</a> has a function named <code>flush</code> whose prototype is as follows:</p>  <pre><code>int (*flush) (struct file *, fl_owner_t id); </code></pre>  <p>My questions are:</p>  <p><strong>Why does we need the second argument?</strong> </p>  <p>Or in other words,</p>  <p><strong>Under what situations must we have the second argument?</strong></p>  <p>Update:</p>  <p>The rationale behind is explained hereï¼š</p>  <p><a href="http://gitlab.mperpetuo.com/it/ipipe/commit/75e1fcc0b18df0a65ab113198e9dc0e98999a08c" rel="nofollow">http://gitlab.mperpetuo.com/it/ipipe/commit/75e1fcc0b18df0a65ab113198e9dc0e98999a08c</a></p>